<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE rdf:RDF [
	<!ENTITY AnnotationVocabulary "https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/meta/AnnotationVocabulary/">
	<!ENTITY dc "http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">
	<!ENTITY owl "http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#">
	<!ENTITY rdf "http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#">
	<!ENTITY rdfs "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#">
	<!ENTITY skos "http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#">
	<!ENTITY terms "http://purl.org/dc/terms/">
	<!ENTITY xsd "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#">
]>
<rdf:RDF xml:base="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/biopharma/MolecularEntity/"
	xmlns:AnnotationVocabulary="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/meta/AnnotationVocabulary/"
	xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"
	xmlns:owl="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#"
	xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
	xmlns:rdfs="http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#"
	xmlns:skos="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#"
	xmlns:terms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/"
	xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#">
	
	<owl:Ontology rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/biopharma/MolecularEntity/">
		<rdfs:label>Molecular Entity</rdfs:label>
		<owl:imports rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/202401/core/Core/"/>
		<owl:versionIRI rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/202501/biopharma/MolecularEntity/"/>
	</owl:Ontology>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AcidBaseIndicatorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularColorIndicatorRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>acid-base indicator role</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_50407</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Acid-base indicators are typically weak acids or weak bases whose conjugate forms differ in color over a characteristic pH transition range. In titration applications, the indicator is selected so that its color change occurs at or near the equivalence point.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular color indicator role that is held by a molecular entity in virtue of that molecular entity being used such that its color indicates a pH range of a material and a change in its color indicates a shift of the material pH into a different pH range</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Aldohexose">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Monosacharide"/>
		<rdfs:label>aldohexose</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_33917</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>six-carbon monosaccharide which in its linear form contains an aldehyde group at position 1</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AminoAcid">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>amino acid</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Alanine; Glycine; Lysine; Glutamic acid</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:33709</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that contains a carboxyl group and one or more amino groups</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AminoAcidResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ChemicalMoiety"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000137"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Peptide">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:someValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>amino acid residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_33708</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>During peptide-bond formation, each amino acid loses the atoms corresponding to one molecule of water. The remaining portion constitutes the amino-acid residue within the polypeptide chain.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>chemical moiety that is a proper part of a peptide and that is the remaining portion of an amino acid resulting from peptide-bond formation</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AminoAcidSequence">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/BiologicalSequence"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000084"/>
				<owl:allValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Peptide">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:allValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>amino acid sequence</rdfs:label>
		<owl:disjointWith rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NucleotideSequence"/>
		<skos:altLabel>peptide sequence</skos:altLabel>
		<skos:altLabel>primary structure sequence</skos:altLabel>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SO_0000104 and https://www.codamono.com/biointerchange/gfvo#PeptideSequence and https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/ich-q-6-b-test-procedures-and-acceptance-criteria-biotechnologicalbiological-products-step-5_en.pdf</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>biological sequence that is the ordered pattern of amino-acid residues that constitute a particular continuous peptide or protein molecule</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AmmoniumIon">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicIon"/>
		<rdfs:label>ammonium ion</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_28938</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>inorganic cation obtained by protonation of ammonia</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Anion">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Ion"/>
		<rdfs:label>anion</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Sulfate ion (SO₄²⁻); Nitrate ion (NO₃⁻); Acetate ion (CH₃COO⁻)</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:22563</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that is a monoatomic or polyatomic species having one or more elementary charges of the electron</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Antibody">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein"/>
		<rdfs:label>antibody</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://tools.thermofisher.com/content/sfs/brochures/1601975-Antibody-Production-Purification-Guide.pdf</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>protein that has the function to selectively bind some antigen</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AntimicrobialAgentRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>antimicrobial agent role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Gentamicin added to cell culture media to prevent bacterial contamination; Benzalkonium chloride included in formulations as a preservative.</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:33281</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role held by a molecular entity when it is added or planned to be added to an environment to kill or inhibit the growth of microorganisms</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AntioxidantRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>antioxidant role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Ascorbic acid (vitamin C) added to media or formulations to prevent oxidation of sensitive components; α-Tocopherol (vitamin E) used to inhibit lipid peroxidation and maintain stability of cell culture supplements or product formulations</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_22586</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Some molecules naturally possess antioxidant activity as a result of their chemical structure. In manufacturing contexts the role is typically recognized (asserted) when that activity is intentionally used, for example when a compound is added to a medium, buffer, or formulation to protect materials, nutrients, or products from oxidation during processing or storage. Such compounds are often included in formulations to maintain the stability of media components, extend product shelf life, or prevent loss of potency during storage.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role held by a molecular entity that is realized in chemical or physiological processes where it counteracts oxidation or inhibits reactions initiated by dioxygen or peroxides</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/BiologicalSequence">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000031"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000084"/>
				<owl:allValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/DeoxyribonucleicAcid">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Peptide">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/RibonucleicAcid">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:allValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>biological sequence</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/IEB/ToolBox/SDKDOCS/BIOSEQ.HTML#:~:text=A%20biological%20sequence%20is%20a,DNA%2C%20RNA%2C%20or%20protein. and http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SO_0000001</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>generically dependent continuant that is the ordered pattern of residues that constitute a particular continuous DNA, RNA, peptide, or protein molecule</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Carbohydrate">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>carbohydrate</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Glucose; Sucrose; Fructose; Lactose; Mannose</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:16646</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Carbohydrates include simple sugars (monosaccharides) such as glucose and fructose, and compounds formed by their condensation, such as disaccharides, oligosaccharides, and polysaccharides. They can also occur in reduced (alditols) or oxidized (acids, aldehydes, ketones) forms, or as modified derivatives in which one or more hydroxy groups are replaced or substituted. Carbohydrates serve as energy sources, structural materials, and signaling molecules in living organisms. Cyclitols, although similar in composition, are generally not considered carbohydrates.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity composed of carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen that consists of or is derived from polyhydroxy aldehydes, ketones, or their condensation products</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/CarbonDioxide">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>carbon dioxide</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_16526</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>organic molecular entity consisting of a carbon atom and two oxygen atoms where the carbon is covalently bonded to each oxygen atom by a double bond</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/CarbonSourceRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularNutrientRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>carbon source role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Glucose as the main carbon source in DMEM or CD-CHO media; Galactose used to control lactate accumulation in CHO cell cultures; Methanol serving as the carbon source in Pichia pastoris expression systems</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.thermofisher.com/ba/en/home/references/gibco-cell-culture-basics/cell-culture-environment/culture-media.html and  https://clinref.com/data/uploads/books/LehningerBiochemistry6thed.pdf and https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11626-017-0186-6</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Carbon sources provide the essential carbon that forms the backbone of cellular structures and fuels metabolic energy production. In mammalian-cell culture, glucose is the primary carbon source, supporting both energy generation and biosynthesis. Alternative substrates such as galactose, fructose, or pyruvate may be used to adjust metabolic fluxes or reduce lactate buildup. In microbial and yeast cultures, carbon sources can include glycerol, sucrose, acetate, or methanol, depending on the organism and process objectives. The selection and concentration of the carbon source directly affect growth, productivity, and by-product formation in manufacturing processes</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of a molecular entity that supplies carbon atoms used by cells to build biomolecules and to generate energy through metabolic pathways such as glycolysis and the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Cation">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Ion"/>
		<rdfs:label>cation</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Potassium ion (K⁺); Calcium ion (Ca²⁺); Ammonium ion (NH₄⁺)</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:36916</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>ion that is a monoatomic or polyatomic species having one or more elementary charges of the proton</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ChelatingAgentRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>chelating agent role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>EDTA in buffer to remove trace metal ions; EGTA in calcium-sensitive assays; citric acid regulating iron in culture media; NTA resin in affinity chromatography for protein purification.</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_38161 and https://www.sigmaaldrich.com/RS/en/technical-documents/technical-article/protein-biology/protein-purification/chelators?srsltid=AfmBOooXIbg6UbKJhWf8NjXdHt19Ktk2E5gud8zwrHR5iuqvICV2jrN8 and https://www.merckmillipore.com/CH/en/products/chemistry-and-biochemicals/biochemicals/chelating-reducing-agents</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:counterExample>Histidine added as a buffering component rather than for chelation; citrate added to adjust pH or provide a carbon source rather than to bind metals; magnesium ions acting as cofactors</AnnotationVocabulary:counterExample>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>1) The environment may be a solution, resin, gel, or other medium in which a metal ion can form coordination bonds.
2) Chelating agents are used for different purposes, such as preventing metal-catalyzed degradation, removing or masking trace metals, maintaining metal ion availability, or supporting analytical and purification steps where metal ions or metal ion bound biomolecules are captured, removed, or released.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role held by a molecular entity when it is added or planned to be added to an environment to bind a particular metal ion through two or more separate coordination sites</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ChemicalMoiety">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000040"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000137"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>chemical moiety</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Fc N-glycan; Phosphate group on serine; Ubiquitin moiety; PEG chain on therapeutic protein;Carboxylate group; Methyl group</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_24433</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:counterExample>Free‐standing molecules (e.g., methane, water); Unbound ions or radicals not attached to a larger entity</AnnotationVocabulary:counterExample>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>material entity consisting of a linked collection of atoms or a single atom and that is a proper continuant part of a molecular entity</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexAGalactosylatedNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>complex agalactosylated N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<owl:disjointWith rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexGalactosylatedNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:complementOf>
							<owl:Restriction>
								<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
								<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GalactoseResidue"/>
							</owl:Restriction>
						</owl:complementOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/guideline-development-production-characterisation-and-specification-monoclonal-antibodies-and-related-products-revision-1_en.pdf and http://www.jbiomed.com/v04p0035.htm and https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4634315/</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>complex N-glycan moiety that has no galactose residues as parts</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexASialylatedNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>complex asialylated N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<owl:disjointWith rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexSialylatedNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:complementOf>
							<owl:Restriction>
								<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
								<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/SialicAcidResidue"/>
							</owl:Restriction>
						</owl:complementOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/guideline-development-production-characterisation-and-specification-monoclonal-antibodies-and-related-products-revision-1_en.pdf and http://www.jbiomed.com/v04p0035.htm and https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4634315/</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>complex N-glycan moiety that has no sialic acid residues as parts</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexAfucosylatedNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>complex afucosylated N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<owl:disjointWith rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexFucosylatedNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:complementOf>
							<owl:Restriction>
								<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
								<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/FucoseResidue"/>
							</owl:Restriction>
						</owl:complementOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/guideline-development-production-characterisation-and-specification-monoclonal-antibodies-and-related-products-revision-1_en.pdf and http://www.jbiomed.com/v04p0035.htm and https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4634315/</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>complex N-glycan moiety that has no fucose residues as parts</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexFucosylatedNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>complex fucosylated N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/FucoseResidue"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/guideline-development-production-characterisation-and-specification-monoclonal-antibodies-and-related-products-revision-1_en.pdf and http://www.jbiomed.com/v04p0035.htm and https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4634315/</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>complex N-glycan moiety that has as part one or more fucose residues</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexGalactosylatedNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>complex galactosylated N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GalactoseResidue"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/guideline-development-production-characterisation-and-specification-monoclonal-antibodies-and-related-products-revision-1_en.pdf and http://www.jbiomed.com/v04p0035.htm and https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4634315/</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>In biopharmaceutical analysis, “galactosylation” refers specifically to the presence of galactose residues on the antennae of complex biantennary N-glycans. Only complex glycans possess two N-acetylglucosamine–initiated antennae capable of receiving galactose, and galactosylation levels are routinely reported as the relative abundance of mono-galactosylated (G1) and di-galactosylated (G2) complex species. Hybrid glycans may carry a single galactose on their GlcNAc-extended arm but are not typcailly categorized as G1 and are not included in % galactosylation calculations. High-mannose glycans cannot be galactosylated. Accordingly, this class applies only to complex N-glycan moieties that contain one or more galactose residues.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>complex N-glycan moiety that has as part one or more galactose residues</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/CorePentasacharideNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>complex N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.sigmaaldrich.com/RS/en/technical-documents/technical-article/protein-biology/protein-labeling-and-modification/n-glycans</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>core pentasacharide N-glycan moeity that extends the conserved N-linked core by adding N-acetylglucosamine residues at both the α-3 and α-6 mannose positions and contains no mannose units beyond those in the core</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycolylneuraminicAcidContainingNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexSialylatedNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>complex N-glycolylneuraminic acid containing N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexSialylatedNGlycanMoeity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NGlycolylneuraminicAcidResidue"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:abbreviation>complex NGNA containing N-glycan moeity</AnnotationVocabulary:abbreviation>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4634315/</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>complex sialylated N-glycan moiety that has as part one or more N-glycolylneuraminic acid (NGNA) residues</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexSialylatedNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>complex sialylated N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ComplexNGlycanMoeity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/SialicAcidResidue"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/guideline-development-production-characterisation-and-specification-monoclonal-antibodies-and-related-products-revision-1_en.pdf and http://www.jbiomed.com/v04p0035.htm and https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4634315/</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>complex N-glycan moiety that has as part one or more sialic acid residues</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/CorePentasacharideNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NGlycanMoiety"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000137"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/N4glycosylLAsparagine"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>core pentasacharide N-glycan moiety</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.sigmaaldrich.com/RS/en/technical-documents/technical-article/protein-biology/protein-labeling-and-modification/n-glycans and https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9781892/</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>1) This class represents the form of N-glycan moiety most commonly encountered in biopharmaceutical glycoproteins, including monoclonal antibodies and other recombinant proteins. All such moieties share the conserved chitobiose core and branched mannose structure that define canonical N-glycans, and they give rise to the high-mannose, hybrid, and complex glycoform families routinely monitored as critical quality attributes in industry analytics. This structural pattern underlies standard glycan annotations such as G0F, G1F, G2F, and high-mannose species
2) Core-pentasaccharide N-glycan moieties occur exclusively at L-asparagine residues in eukaryotic glycoproteins which is reflected in the necessary condition of it being a part of N4-glycosyl-L-asparagine</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>N-glycan moiety that contains the core pentasaccharide Man₃GlcNAc₂, consisting of a di-N-acetyl-chitobiose unit extended by a branched mannose trisaccharide</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/DeamidatedResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ModifiedAminoAcidResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>deamidated residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MOD_00400</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>This modification corresponds to deamidation of an amino acid residue such as asparagine or glutamine. The reaction converts the side-chain amide to a carboxyl group, typically yielding aspartate or glutamate within the peptide.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>modified amino acid residue that results from conversion of a carboxamido group to a carboxyl group, involving a net gain of oxygen and a loss of nitrogen and hydrogen</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/DeoxyribonucleicAcid">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NucleicAcid"/>
		<rdfs:label>deoxyribonucleic acid</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:acronym>DNA</AnnotationVocabulary:acronym>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_16991</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>nucleic acid that is composed of nucleotides containing deoxyribose</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Dioxygen">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>dioxygen</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_15379</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>inorganic molecular entity consisting of two oxygen atoms covalently bonded to each other</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Endotoxin">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Toxin"/>
		<rdfs:label>endotoxin</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Lipopolysaccharide">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/hasRole"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EndotoxinRole"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>See the expanded definition under the corresponding role class.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>lipopolysaccharide with an endotoxin role</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EndotoxinRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ToxinRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>endotoxin role</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.thermofisher.com/rs/en/home/life-science/protein-biology/protein-purification-isolation/protein-purification/endotoxin-quantitation-removal.html” and https://www.biophorum.com/download/cvp-case-study-interactive-version/ and https://www.fda.gov/regulatory-information/search-fda-guidance-documents/guidance-industry-pyrogen-and-endotoxins-testing-questions-and-answers”</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>1) The role excludes protein exotoxins, viral agents, ion toxins, inorganic poisons, non-microbial pyrogens, ions, and non-viable particulate matter.
2) For biologics manufacturing, the endotoxin role identifies lipopolysaccharide impurities originating from Gram-negative bacteria that must be quantified and limited in material samples, single-use parts, buffers, purification pools, or in-process holds, based on pyrogen-safety acceptance thresholds, as part of sterility assurance and GMP batch decisions. Endotoxin control is assessed under a corresponding sample-level measurable attribute (e.g., endotoxin load), which supports contamination risk mitigation, process comparability across sites, in-process filtration and purification hold points, and product release decisions.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>toxin role held by a lipopolysaccharide (LPS) that originates from Gram-negative bacterial cellular material</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnergySubstrateRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularNutrientRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>energy substrate role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Glucose serving as the main energy substrate in DMEM or RPMI 1640 cell-culture media; Glutamine acting as both an energy and nitrogen source in chemically defined CHO-cell feeds; Glycerol used as an energy substrate in E. coli fermentation media</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://clinref.com/data/uploads/books/LehningerBiochemistry6thed.pdf and https://aiche.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1021/bp00036a010 and https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/biochemistry-genetics-and-molecular-biology/energy-metabolism</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>In manufacturing and culture systems, glucose and glutamine are the most common energy substrates supporting mammalian cell growth and productivity. Depending on process conditions, other compounds such as lactate, pyruvate, or specific amino acids may also serve as energy sources. The type and concentration of energy substrates influence cell metabolism, product quality, and process performance, making their control a key part of medium and feed design.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of a molecular entity that serves as a source of metabolic energy by undergoing enzymatic conversion in cellular pathways that generate adenosine triphosphate (ATP) or reducing equivalents required for growth, maintenance, and biosynthesis</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeActivatorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeRegulatorRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>enzyme activator role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Magnesium ions enhancing the activity of DNA and RNA polymerases; Chloride ions activating salivary amylase; Potassium ions increasing pyruvate kinase activity; Calcium ions promoting protease and phospholipase activation</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:195252</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role held by a molecular entity that is realized in an enzyme-catalyzed reaction through increasing the catalytic activity of the enzyme</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeCofactorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeRegulatorRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>enzyme cofactor role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Magnesium ions stabilizing ATP in kinase reactions; Zinc ions required for the catalytic activity of alcohol dehydrogenase; Flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD) acting as an electron carrier in redox enzymes; Heme supporting oxidation reactions within cytochrome oxidase</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:23357</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>enzyme functional regulator role held by a molecular entity that is realized in an enzymatic reaction through enabling the catalytic activity of a particular enzyme</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeInhibitorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeRegulatorRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>enzyme inhibitor role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Aprotinin added to cell culture media to inhibit serine proteases and prevent product degradation; Sodium fluoride inhibiting enolase in glycolytic pathways; Cyanide binding to cytochrome oxidase and blocking electron transport</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:23924</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role held by a material entity that is realized in an enzyme-catalyzed reaction through decreasing or preventing the catalytic activity of the enzyme</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeRegulatorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularActivityRegulatorRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>enzyme regulator role</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/TXPO_0003722 and http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0030234</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of a molecular entity that binds to an enzyme and modulates its catalytic activity without causing covalent modification of the enzyme</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/FucoseResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MonosacharideResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>fucose residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>monosacharide residue that is the remaining portion of fucose</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Galactose">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Aldohexose"/>
		<rdfs:label>galactose</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_28260</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>aldohexose that is the C-4 epimer of glucose</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GalactoseResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MonosacharideResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>galactose residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>monosacharide residue that is the remaining portion of galactose</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Glucose">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Aldohexose"/>
		<rdfs:label>glucose</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_17234</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>aldohexose used as a source of energy and metabolic intermediate</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycatedResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycoconjugatedResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>glycated residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MOD_00767</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>glyconjugated residue that is a Schiff-base or Amadori ketosamine adduct resulting from the covalent attachment of a reducing sugar to the amino group of an amino-acid residue through non-enzymatic reaction</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycoconjugatedResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ModifiedAminoAcidResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>glycoconjugated residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MOD_00764</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>modified amino acid residue that results from covalent attachment of a carbohydrate-like group, either through enzymatic formation of a glycosidic bond or through non-enzymatic glycation involving formation of a Schiff-base or Amadori-type ketosamine adduct</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Glycoprotein">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein"/>
		<rdfs:label>glycoprotein</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycosylatedResidue"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PR_000037069</AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>protein that includes at least one glycosylated residue</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycosylatedResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycoconjugatedResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>glycosylated residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MOD_00693</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>This subclass differs from glycation-derived glycoconjugated residues because the carbohydrate-like group is attached through a glycosidic bond at a position originally occupied by a hydrogen atom. Such glycosidic attachments are produced by enzymatic glycosylation pathways in the endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi apparatus and represent regulated post-translational modifications. In contrast, glycation-derived residues arise through non-enzymatic reactions during manufacturing or storage that form Schiff-base or Amadori-type ketosamine adducts and do not involve Golgi-dependent enzymatic processes.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>glycoconjugated residue that results from replacement of a hydrogen atom with a carbohydrate-like group through formation of a glycosidic bond</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GrowthFactor">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>growth factor</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Peptide">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/hasRole"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GrowthFactorRole"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<skos:example>Vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) promoting endothelial proliferation; Insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) enhancing recombinant protein production in mammalian cells</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0008083</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>See the expanded definition under the corresponding role class.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>protein or peptide with a growth factor role</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GrowthFactorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularMessengerRole"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/roleOf"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Peptide">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:someValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>growth factor role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) promoting endothelial proliferation; Insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) enhancing recombinant protein production in mammalian cells</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0008083</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>In culture media and biomanufacturing formulations, this role is typically recognized (asserted) when a protein or peptide is intentionally added to support proliferation, maintain viability, or enhance productivity</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role held by a protein or peptide that is realized in signaling processes where it stimulates cellular growth or proliferation through receptor-mediated mechanisms.</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/HeterodimericAntibody">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Antibody"/>
		<rdfs:label>heterodimeric antibody</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>antibody consisting of two light chains and two heavy chains, where the heavy chains are different from each other</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/HighMannoseNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/CorePentasacharideNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>high mannose N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.sigmaaldrich.com/RS/en/technical-documents/technical-article/protein-biology/protein-labeling-and-modification/n-glycans</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>core pentasacharide N-glycan moiety that contains unsubstituted terminal mannose units and whose total mannose count is typically between five and nine</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/HomodimericAntibody">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Antibody"/>
		<rdfs:label>homodimeric antibody</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>antibody consisting of two identical heavy chains and two identical light chains</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Hormone">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>hormone</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/hasRole"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/HormoneRole"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<skos:example>Insulin acting as a regulator of glucose metabolism and anabolic activity; Hydrocortisone included in formulations to maintain epithelial cell differentiation and reduce stress responses; Triiodothyronine (T₃) supplemented to stimulate protein synthesis and enhance metabolic activity; Estradiol incorporated to regulate gene expression in hormone-responsive production cell lines</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_24621</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>See the expanded definition under the corresponding role class.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>organic molecular entity with a hormone role</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/HormoneRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularMessengerRole"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/roleOf"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>hormone role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Insulin acting as a regulator of glucose metabolism and anabolic activity; Hydrocortisone included in formulations to maintain epithelial cell differentiation and reduce stress responses; Triiodothyronine (T₃) supplemented to stimulate protein synthesis and enhance metabolic activity; Estradiol incorporated to regulate gene expression in hormone-responsive production cell lines</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_24621</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>1) Some molecules naturally act as hormones in living systems by binding to receptors and influencing cell metabolism, growth, or gene expression. . In  formulation and culture contexts the role is typically recognized (asserted) when that activity is intentionally used. For example when a compound is added to a medium, buffer, or formulation to promote cell proliferation, maintain differentiation, or regulate metabolic balance.
2) Although originally defined as endogenous substances synthesized by specialized cells or glands and transported to target sites, the term now also includes semi-synthetic and fully synthetic compounds that mimic or modify natural hormonal activity.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role held by an organic molecular entity that is realized in cellular signaling or regulatory processes where it modulates the activity or metabolism of cells or tissues through receptor-mediated mechanisms</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/HybridNGlycanMoeity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/CorePentasacharideNGlycanMoeity"/>
		<rdfs:label>hybrid N-glycan moeity</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.sigmaaldrich.com/RS/en/technical-documents/technical-article/protein-biology/protein-labeling-and-modification/n-glycans</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>core pentasacharide N-glycan moeity that contains both unsubstituted terminal mannose residues and at least one mannose residue substituted by an N-acetylglucosamine unit</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicAnion">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Anion"/>
		<rdfs:label>inorganic anion</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Phosphate ion (PO₄³⁻)</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:24834</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>anion of an inorganic molecular entity</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicIon">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Cation"/>
		<rdfs:label>inorganic cation</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Sodium ion (Na⁺); Chloride ion (Cl⁻); Magnesium ion (Mg²⁺);</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:36915</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>cation of an inorganic molecular entity</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicMolecularEntity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>inorganic molecular entity</rdfs:label>
		<owl:disjointWith rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<skos:example>Water (H₂O); Ammonia (NH₃); Carbon dioxide (CO₂); Nitric oxide (NO)</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:24835</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that contains no carbon</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Insulin">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Polypeptide"/>
		<rdfs:label>insulin</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_145810</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Insulin as a process-related impurity: In biopharmaceutical production, insulin is commonly employed in cell culture media as a growth-promoting supplement; when not fully removed during downstream purification, residual insulin may persist in the final drug substance or drug product. Its presence must be carefully monitored because it constitutes a non-intended material introduced during processing, and could impact final product safety, stability or bioactivity. Ensuring adequate clearance of residual insulin is therefore part of the impurity control strategy and aligns with regulatory expectations for process-related residuals</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>polypeptide that consists of two polypeptide chains, A chain and B chain, linked by disulfide bonds</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Ion">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>ion</rdfs:label>
		<owl:disjointWith rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Salt"/>
		<skos:example>Hydrogen ion (H⁺); Chloride ion (Cl⁻); Sodium ion (Na⁺); Ammonium ion (NH₄⁺)</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:24870</AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity having a net electric charge</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/LGlutamicAcid">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ProteinogenicAminoAcid"/>
		<rdfs:label>L-glutamic acid</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_16015</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>proteogenic amino acid that is glutaric acid bearing a single amino substituent at position 2</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/LGlutamine">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ProteinogenicAminoAcid"/>
		<rdfs:label>L-glutamine</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:18050</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>proteinogenic amino acid that consists of butyric acid bearing an amino substituent at position 2 and a carbamoyl substituent at position 4</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/LGlutatmateOneMinus">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicAnion"/>
		<rdfs:label>L-glutamate(1-)</rdfs:label>
		<skos:altLabel>L-glutamate monoanion</skos:altLabel>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_29985</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>organic anion that is the conjugate base of L-glutamic acid, having anionic carboxy groups and a cationic amino group</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Lactate">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicAnion"/>
		<rdfs:label>lactate</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_24996</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>organic anion that is the conjugate base of lactic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Lipid">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>lipid</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Phosphatidylcholine; Cholesterol; Triglyceride; Sphingomyelin</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_18059</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that is a biologically derived organic compound that is soluble in nonpolar solvents and includes fats, oils, phospholipids, steroids, and related molecule</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/LipidPrecursorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularNutrientRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>lipid precursor role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Ethanolamine serving as a precursor for phosphatidylethanolamine synthesis in mammalian cells; Choline functioning as a precursor for phosphatidylcholine</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://pub.uni-bielefeld.de/record/2943695 and https://clinref.com/data/uploads/books/LehningerBiochemistry6thed.pdf</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Lipid precursors are small metabolites that serve as the starting materials for lipid biosynthesis. Their availability determines the rate and composition of lipid formation, influencing membrane structure, energy storage, and signaling balance. In cell culture and biomanufacturing, maintaining sufficient lipid precursor supply supports membrane biogenesis, cell growth, and product secretion.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of a molecular entity that provides carbon or functional groups required for the biosynthetic formation of complex lipids such as fatty acids, phospholipids, or sterols</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Lipopolysaccharide">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>lipopolysaccharide</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_16412</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>organic molecular entity consisting of a trisaccharide repeating unit (two heptose units and octulosonic acid) with oligosaccharide side chains and 3-hydroxytetradecanoic acid units</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MannoseResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MonosacharideResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>mannose residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>monosacharide residue that is the remaining portion of mannose</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ModifiedAminoAcidResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AminoAcidResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>modified amino acid residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PR_000025513</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>This class includes amino acid residues that have undergone a covalent change such as oxidation, reduction, alkylation, acylation, or other modification to their side-chain or backbone atoms while remaining part of an intact peptide. The class does not include moieties that result from cleavage of the peptide backbone or from replacement of the original amino acid at that position</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>amino acid residue that results from covalent modification of the side-chain or backbone atoms of an amino acid residue, where the modification maintains the integrity of the peptide containing that residue</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularActivityRegulatorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>molecular activity regulator role</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0098772 and http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/TXPO_0003713</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>This role applies to molecular entities that alter or fine-tune the activity of enzymes, receptors, channels, or other molecular targets by mechanisms such as allosteric binding, competitive inhibition, or conformational stabilization.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of a molecular entity that modulates the activity of another molecule through non-covalent interactions that do not result in covalent modification of the target</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularColorIndicatorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularVisualIndicatorRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>molecular color indicator role</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_50410</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular visual indicator role that is held by a molecular entity in virtue of that molecular entity being used such that a change in its color indicates the presence, amount, or state of a specified substance or quality</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000040"/>
		<rdfs:label>molecular entity</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>ion; salt; amino acid; protein; antibody</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_23367</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>material entity that is a constitutionally or isotopically distinct atom, molecule, ion, ion pair, radical, radical ion, complex, conformer etc., identifiable as a separately distinguishable entity</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityPopulation">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000027"/>
		<rdfs:label>molecular entity population</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000027">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000115"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000115"/>
						<owl:allValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>object aggregate which only has molecular entities as its member parts</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000023"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/roleOf"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>molecular entity role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>EDTA acting as a chelating agent in buffers to remove trace metal ions; Vitamin C acting as an antioxidant in media or formulations to prevent oxidation of sensitive components.</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_50906</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>This role represents context-dependent behaviors of molecules such as binding, catalysis, inhibition, or signaling. It corresponds to the use of “role” in CHEBI and is used to describe realizable molecular behaviors in chemical or biological environments.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of a molecular entity that reflects a specific chemical or biochemical behavior it may exhibit under certain condition</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularIndicatorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>molecular indicator role</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_47867</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>The observable change is often visual (e.g., color change), but may also be a non-visual detectable signal (e.g., fluorescence, change in absorbance, change in luminescence, change in electrical signal, or change in emitted or absorbed radiation)</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity role that is held by a molecular entity in virtue of that molecular entity being used such that an observable change in that molecular entity indicates the presence, amount, or state of a specified substance or quality</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularMessengerRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>molecular messenger role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Insulin added to cell culture medium to promote glucose uptake and anabolic metabolism; epidermal growth factor (EGF) added to serum-free media to stimulate cell proliferation</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_33280 and https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538154/</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of a molecular entity that transmits signals between cells, tissues, or organs, enabling communication and coordination of biological processes</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularNutrientRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>molecular nutrient role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Glucose serving as a carbon and energy source in mammalian cell-culture media;Choline acting as a lipid precursor in the synthesis of phosphatidylcholine for membrane formation;Ammonium ion serving as a nitrogen source in microbial fermentation media</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>This role narrows the CHEBI concept of a nutrient to the molecular level. It applies to molecules required for sustaining metabolic function that organisms cannot synthesize, or cannot synthesize in adequate amounts, under normal physiological or cultivation conditions. Such molecules are provided externally through culture media, feed formulations, or the surrounding environment.</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_33284</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of a molecular entity that supports cellular metabolism, growth, or maintenance through its participation in biochemical processes and that must be supplied from an external source when endogenous synthesis is absent or insufficient</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularVisualIndicatorRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularIndicatorRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>molecular visual indicator role</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_50408</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Visual change” includes changes in color, opacity/clarity, or emission (e.g., fluorescence)</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular indicator role that is held by a molecular entity in virtue of that molecular entity being used such that a visual change in that molecular entity indicates the presence, amount, or state of a specified substance or quality</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Monosacharide">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Carbohydrate"/>
		<rdfs:label>monosacharide</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_35381</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>carbohydrate that consists of a single polyhydroxy aldehyde or polyhydroxy ketone unit with three or more carbon atoms and is not glycosidically linked to another carbohydrate unit</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MonosacharideResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ChemicalMoiety"/>
		<rdfs:label>monosacharide residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_78848</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>chemical moiety that is a proper part of an oligo- or polysaccharide, or of their residues, and that is the remaining portion of a monosaccharide after formation of a glycosidic bond</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/N4glycosylLAsparagine">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NGlycosylatedResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>N4-glycosyl-L-asparagine</rdfs:label>
		<skos:altLabel>N-Glycosyl-L-asparagine</skos:altLabel>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MOD_00160 and http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_59108</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>The term “N4-glycosyl-L-asparagine” follows the classical IUPAC atom-numbering scheme, in which the side-chain amide nitrogen of L-asparagine is designated as N4. This nitrogen is the site of N-linked glycosylation.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>N-glycosylated residue that results from covalent attachment of a glycan to the side-chain nitrogen of an L-asparagine residue</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NGlycanMoiety">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ChemicalMoiety"/>
		<rdfs:label>N-glycan moiety</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_59520</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>chemical moiety that is the remaining portion of a glycan resulting from its covalent attachment to the side-chain nitrogen of an asparagine or arginine residue</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NGlycolylneuraminicAcidResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/SialicAcidResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>N-glycolylneuraminic acid residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:abbreviation>NGNA residue</AnnotationVocabulary:abbreviation>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>sialic acid residue that is the remaining portion of N-glycolylneuraminic acid residue</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NGlycosylatedResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycosylatedResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>N-glycosylated residue</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycosylatedResidue">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NGlycanMoiety"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MOD_00006</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>This class includes amino acid residues, most commonly asparagine, that acquire a covalently attached carbohydrate-like group through an N-glycosidic linkage. N-glycosylation is generated by enzymatic glycosylation pathways in the endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi apparatus and yields N-linked glycans with characteristic core structures.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>glycosylated residue that results from replacement of a hydrogen atom on a nitrogen atom with a carbohydrate-like group through formation of an N-glycosidic bond</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NitrogenSourceRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularNutrientRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>nitrogen source role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Glutamine acting as the primary nitrogen source in CHO and hybridoma culture media; Ammonium ion serving as a nitrogen source in microbial fermentation media</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/0168165689900096 and https://clinref.com/data/uploads/books/LehningerBiochemistry6thed.pdf</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Nitrogen sources provide the assimilable nitrogen required to build cellular macromolecules and maintain metabolic activity. In mammalian-cell culture, amino acids and glutamine are typically the main nitrogen sources, supporting both biosynthesis and energy metabolism. In microbial and yeast media, nitrogen sources commonly include ammonium salts, nitrates, or urea. The type and concentration of nitrogen source influence growth kinetics, intracellular pH, energy demand, and by-product formation, making nitrogen management critical in media and feed formulation.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of a molecular entity that supplies usable nitrogen atoms for the synthesis of amino acids, nucleotides, and other nitrogen-containing biomolecules essential for cell growth and function</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NonProteinogenicAminoAcid">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AminoAcid"/>
		<rdfs:label>non-proteinogenic amino acid</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Ornithine; Citrulline; β-alanine; 4-hydroxyproline</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:83820</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>amino acid that is not encoded by the genetic code of any organism and therefore cannot be incorporated into a polypeptide chain during translation</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NucleicAcid">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>nucleic acid</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_33696</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>organic molecular entity composed of two or more nucleotides linked by phosphodiester bonds</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Nucleoside">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>nucleoside</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Adenosine; Cytidine; Guanosine; Uridine</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:33838</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>The nucleobase is typically adenine, guanine, cytosine, thymine, uracil, or xanthine. The sugar component is usually ribose or deoxyribose, forming an N-glycosidic bond.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that consists of a nucleobase linked through a nitrogen atom to a sugar such as ribose or deoxyribose.</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Nucleotide">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>nucleotide</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Adenosine triphosphate (ATP); Guanosine monophosphate (GMP); Cytidine triphosphate (CTP)</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:36976</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>A nucleotide includes three structural components: a nitrogen-containing base, a pentose sugar (ribose or deoxyribose), and one or more phosphate groups linked to the sugar, typically at the 5′ position.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that consists of a nucleoside having one or more phosphate groups attached to its sugar moiety</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NucleotideSequence">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/BiologicalSequence"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000084"/>
				<owl:allValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/DeoxyribonucleicAcid">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/RibonucleicAcid">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:allValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>nucleotide sequence</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_C45374</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>biological sequence that is the ordered pattern of nucleotide residues that constitute a particular continuous DNA or RNA molecule</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OGlycanMoiety">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ChemicalMoiety"/>
		<rdfs:label>O-glycan moiety</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_59521</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>chemical moiety that is the remaining portion of a glycan resulting from its covalent attachment to the side-chain hydroxyl oxygen of a serine, threonine, hydroxylysine, or hydroxyproline residue</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OGlycosylatedResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycosylatedResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>O-glycosylated residue</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GlycosylatedResidue">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OGlycanMoiety"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MOD_00396</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>This class includes amino acid residues, most commonly serine and threonine, that acquire a covalently attached carbohydrate-like group through an O-glycosidic linkage.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>glycosylated residue that results from replacement of a hydrogen atom on an oxygen atom with a carbohydrate-like group through formation of an O-glycosidic bond</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicAnion">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Anion"/>
		<rdfs:label>organic anion</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_25696</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>anion of an organic molecular entity</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicCation">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Cation"/>
		<rdfs:label>organic cation</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_25697</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>cation of an organic molecular entity</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>organic molecular entity</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Ethanol; Acetic acid; Glucose; Lactic acid; Albumin;Estradiol</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:50860</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that contains carbon</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OxidizedResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ModifiedAminoAcidResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>oxidized residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MOD_00675</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>modified amino acid residue that results from covalent changes involving loss of hydrogen atoms or addition of oxygen atoms to the residue</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Peptide">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>peptide</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Glutathione; Oxytocin; Bradykinin; Angiotensin II</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:16670</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>A peptide is an amide formed through the condensation of amino acids, producing covalent linkages known as peptide bonds. The term generally refers to structures composed of α-amino acids but may also include those derived from other amino acid types.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity formed from two or more amino acids by the formation of amide bonds between the carboxyl group of one and the amino group of another</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/PolySacharide">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Carbohydrate"/>
		<rdfs:label>polysacharide</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_18154</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>This term is commonly used only for those containing more than ten monosaccharide residues.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>carbohydrate consisting of large numbers of monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Polyamine">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>polyamine</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Putrescine; Spermidine; Spermine</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:88061</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that is an organic amino compound that contains two or more amino groups</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Polypeptide">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Peptide"/>
		<rdfs:label>polypeptide</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Casein; Collagen fragment; Insulin chain A; β-lactoglobulin</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:15841</AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>peptide containing ten or more amino acid residues</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/PotassiumIon">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicIon"/>
		<rdfs:label>potassium ion</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_29103</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>monoatomic monocation obtained from potassium</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000110"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Polypeptide"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>protein</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Albumin; Monoclonal antibody (IgG); Recombinant human growth hormone</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_36080 and https://www.fda.gov/media/122985/download</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>From FDA Definition of the Term “Biological Product” : “protein” means “any alpha amino acid polymer with a specific, defined sequence that is greater than 40 amino acids in size</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that is a biological macromolecule minimally consisting of one polypeptide chain synthesized at the ribosome</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ProteinAggregate">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000111"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ProteinFragment">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:someValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>protein aggregate</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Soluble antibody HMW clusters observed by SEC; freeze-stress induced protein dimers tethered by disulfides; inclusion bodies in microbial cytoplasm; prion clumps in neural tissue</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5392216/ and http://id.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/D066329 and http://biomodels.net/SBO/SBO_0000543 and https://www.fda.gov/media/85017/download</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:counterExample>mAb monomer; ribosome; nucleosome</AnnotationVocabulary:counterExample>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>1) Aggregates can form through diverse mechanisms including non-covalent self-association, misfolding, interfacial, environmental, or mechanical stresses, or via covalent links that are not peptide bonds. 
2) The class includes assemblies formed from any mixture of folded, partially folded, misfolded, or unfolded proteins
3) Aggregates may appear intracellularly or extracellularly. 
4) The term is neutral to function (or lack thereof), solubility, and precipitation state, which are modeled separately when relevant. 
5) The term covers aggregates that are transient, stable, soluble, insoluble, precipitating, or non-precipitating.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>organic molecular entity that consists of physical coalescence of two or more protein molecules and/or protein fragments without forming new peptide bonds between the proteins</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ProteinFragment">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Peptide">
					</rdf:Description>
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein">
					</rdf:Description>
				</owl:unionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000175"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Protein"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>protein fragment</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.bioprocessintl.com/formulation/stability-considerations-for-biopharmaceuticals-overview-of-protein-and-peptide-degradation-pathways and https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5392216/ and https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/documents/scientific-guideline/guideline-development-production-characterisation-and-specification-monoclonal-antibodies-and-related-products-revision-1_en.pdf</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>1) The phrase “was a proper part of a protein” captures that the fragment existed as a proper part before the cleavage. After the bond-breaking event, it persists as an independent entity.
2) Peptide-bond cleavage that generates fragments may occur through spontaneous or enzyme-driven bond disruption. Examples include hydrolysis under chemical or environmental stress, agitation or proteolytic activity.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>peptide or protein that was a proper part of a protein molecule and that is a result of cleavage of one or more peptide bonds within that protein</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ProteinogenicAminoAcid">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/AminoAcid"/>
		<rdfs:label>proteinogenic amino acid</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Serine; Methionine; Phenylalanine; Tryptophan</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:83813</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>amino acid that is a precursor to proteins and can thus be incorporated into a polypeptide chain during translation</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/RibonucleicAcid">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/NucleicAcid"/>
		<rdfs:label>ribonucleic acid</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:acronym>RNA</AnnotationVocabulary:acronym>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_33697</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>nucleic acid that is composed of nucleotide units containing ribose</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Ribonucleoside">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Nucleoside"/>
		<rdfs:label>ribonucleoside</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:18254</AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>nucleoside where the sugar component is D-ribose</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Salt">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000110"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Anion"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000110"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Cation"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>salt</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>sodium chloride; sodium monophosphate; potassium acetate</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:24866</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity that is an assembly of cations and anions</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/SialicAcidResidue">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MonosacharideResidue"/>
		<rdfs:label>sialic acid residue</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>monosacharide residue that is the remaining portion of sialic acid</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/SodiumIon">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicIon"/>
		<rdfs:label>sodium ion</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_29101</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>monoatomic monocation obtained from sodium</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Steroid">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Lipid"/>
		<rdfs:label>steroid</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Estradiol; Testosterone; Cortisol</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:35341</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>1) Additional side chains or functional groups may be attached to the core rings, and the rings may be hydrogenated or slightly modified by rearrangement.
2) Steroids include naturally occurring compounds and synthetic analogues. This class encompasses sterols (e.g., cholesterol), bile acids, and steroid hormones, as well as numerous synthetic derivatives with medicinal applications.
3) Chemically, steroids are compounds derived from the cyclopenta[a]phenanthrene skeleton, typically with methyl groups at C-10 and C-13 and often an alkyl side chain at C-17. Natural steroids arise from squalene and may show partial hydrogenation or minor ring modifications.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>lipid that has a core structure of four fused carbon rings made up of three six-membered rings and one five-membered ring</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Toxin">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>toxin</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/hasRole"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ToxinRole"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>See the expanded definition under the corresponding role class.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity with a toxin role</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/ToxinRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularEntityRole"/>
		<rdfs:label>toxin role</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_27026 and http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IDO_0000426</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>A molecular entity bearing a toxin role is distinguished by its capacity to cause disturbance when introduced or absorbed in sufficient quantity. This may include: (i) malfunction of cells; (ii) damage to the extracellular matrix; or (iii) cell damage to a degree that can lead to cell loss or cell death.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>molecular entity role held by a molecular entity that can cause disturbance to an organism or a cell by chemical reaction or other activity on the molecular scale, when present in sufficient quantity</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/TraceElementRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularNutrientRole"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/roleOf"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicAnion">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicIon">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:someValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>trace element role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Fe²⁺ salt added to media as part of a trace element supplement; Cu²⁺ from CuSO₄·5H₂O (copper sulfate pentahydrate) added to support oxidative enzyme function</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>https://aiche.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/btpr.3368 and https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30290072/ and https://pub.uni-bielefeld.de/record/2943695</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>1)Trace elements are essential metal or metalloid ions that enable catalytic activity, electron transfer, or structural stabilization of biomolecules. They cannot be synthesized by cells and are typically provided as inorganic salts, oxoanions, or chelates that release bioavailable ions such as Fe²⁺, Zn²⁺, Cu²⁺, Mn²⁺, Co²⁺, or SeO₃²⁻. 
2) Most trace elements are transition metals, while some, like selenium, are metalloids. 
3)While they are often intentionally added to culture media, they may also originate from raw material impurities, leachables, or water quality and still fulfill their biological role. In such cases, an ion may bear both a trace element role and an impurity role, depending on its origin and concentration.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of an inorganic ion that is required in small amounts to support enzymatic, structural, or regulatory functions in cells and that must be supplied externally</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Uridine">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Ribonucleoside"/>
		<rdfs:label>uridine</rdfs:label>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/CHEBI:16704</AnnotationVocabulary:directSource>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>ribonucleoside composed of a molecule of uracil attached to a ribofuranose moiety via a β‒N1-glycosidic bond</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/Vitamin">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>vitamin</rdfs:label>
		<owl:equivalentClass>
			<owl:Class>
				<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
					<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity">
					</rdf:Description>
					<owl:Restriction>
						<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/hasRole"/>
						<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/VitaminRole"/>
					</owl:Restriction>
				</owl:intersectionOf>
			</owl:Class>
		</owl:equivalentClass>
		<skos:example>Thiamine (vitamin B₁) supporting carbohydrate metabolism;Riboflavin (vitamin B₂) serving as precursor of flavin cofactors (FAD, FMN); Biotin acting in carboxylation reactions.</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_33229</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>See the expanded definition under the corresponding role class.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>organic molecular entity with a vitamin role</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/VitaminRole">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/MolecularNutrientRole"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/Core/roleOf"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/OrganicMolecularEntity"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>vitamin role</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Thiamine (vitamin B₁) supporting carbohydrate metabolism;Riboflavin (vitamin B₂) serving as precursor of flavin cofactors (FAD, FMN); Biotin acting in carboxylation reactions.</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_33229</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Vitamins are essential organic compounds that enable or regulate metabolic and physiological processes, usually by serving as cofactors, coenzyme precursors, or regulatory metabolites. They are required only in small amounts but cannot be synthesized or activated in sufficient quantities without external inputs such as nutrient supplementation or environmental factors like light. In human and animal nutrition, vitamins are obtained through dietary intake; in biomanufacturing, they are incorporated into culture media to maintain cell viability and productivity.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>role of an organic molecular entity that is required in small amounts to sustain normal metabolic or physiological functions and whose adequate supply depends on external sources or environmental conditions</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/WaterMolecule">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/InorganicMolecularEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label>water molecule</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>H₂O (ordinary water);D₂O (heavy water);HDO (semi-heavy water)</skos:example>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_15377</AnnotationVocabulary:adaptedFrom>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>Water (H₂O) is a simple inorganic molecule that serves as the fundamental solvent and medium for physical, chemical, and biological processes.
In biomanufacturing and laboratory environments, materials composed primarily of water are used for diverse purposes including reagent preparation, cleaning, and process operations.
While the molecule itself is chemically well defined, the various grades of water used in industry (such as Purified Water and Water for Injection) represent processed materials distinguished by their purity, microbial limits, and intended use, rather than distinct molecular forms.
Water may also occur in isotopic variants, such as heavy water (D₂O) or semi-heavy water (HDO), which share the same molecular structure but differ in hydrogen isotope composition.</AnnotationVocabulary:explanatoryNote>
		<AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>inorganic molecular entity consisting of an oxygen atom that is covalently bonded to two hydrogen atoms</AnnotationVocabulary:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:AllDisjointClasses>
		<owl:members rdf:parseType="Collection">
			<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeActivatorRole">
			</rdf:Description>
			<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeCofactorRole">
			</rdf:Description>
			<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/EnzymeInhibitorRole">
			</rdf:Description>
		</owl:members>
	</owl:AllDisjointClasses>
	<owl:AllDisjointClasses>
		<owl:members rdf:parseType="Collection">
			<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/FucoseResidue">
			</rdf:Description>
			<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/GalactoseResidue">
			</rdf:Description>
			<rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/SialicAcidResidue">
			</rdf:Description>
		</owl:members>
	</owl:AllDisjointClasses>
</rdf:RDF>